# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
I thought this would be easier than it was, given that JavaScript has the `instanceof` keyword! Boy was that wrong :)

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- I started out by feeling out the equality expected in the test cases (which ended up being *semantic* equality), and tried to use `instanceof` until the very end.

- There ended up being so many edge cases to `instanceof` that I scrapped it and wrote a tree walker. That ended up feeling like the *intended* solution so it worked out.

# After Thoughts
- For simple comparisons where there are no literals involved - such as a React component `useEffect` checking if an elmenent is `instanceof HtmlInputElement` you're good to go. But for a catch-all function this is almost too broad for its own good.
- Checking if `5n` is and instance of `Object` is not really all that helpful and you would be way better of with one-off checks like `isBigInt` or `isArray` like I have made for applications in the past.
- Granted, you could always add a `<T, O>(): T is O => {}` gate and this might be more useful if you would otherwise have tons of util functions for instance checking :)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n)$$, where $$n$$ is the potential comparison depth of the prototype chain of `obj`. Deep inheritance will take longer than shallow!

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(1)$$, constant space, as it does not utilize any data structures that grow with the input size

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {any} obj
 * @param {any} classFunction
 * @return {boolean}
 */
var checkIfInstanceOf = function (obj, classFunction) {
  // Null and Undefined are problematic, just return false
  if (obj === null || classFunction === null) return false;
  if (obj === undefined || classFunction === undefined) return false;

  // This is far more reliable than instanceof if you're looking for deep prototype equality
  let objProto = Object.getPrototypeOf(obj);
  while (objProto !== null) {
    // Note, this can - and will! - return here if it's an easy comparison
    if (objProto == classFunction.prototype) {
      return true;
    } else {
      objProto = Object.getPrototypeOf(objProto);
    }
  }

  // if you get here, return false
  return false;
};
```

