solutions.content:
A naive approach to this question would be to do ```return obj instanceof classFunction```

To understand why just calling instanceof fails, we need to understand what the question is actually asking.

Let's say we have some objects like this:
```
function Parent() {}

function Child() {}
Child.prototype = Object.create(Parent.prototype);
Child.prototype.constructor = Child;

function Grandchild() {}
Grandchild.prototype = Object.create(Child.prototype);
Grandchild.prototype.constructor = Grandchild;

let child = new Child();
let grandchild = new Grandchild();
```

In this case, Child is a... child... of Parent. And Grandchild is a child of Child. As a result, Grandchild contains all the methods of Parent.

The questions defines an "instance" of a class as any object that contains that class's methods.
If we were to do ```instanceof child```, we would just get back "Child". But as the question is written, Child, and Grandchild, would both be instances of Parent, as both contain Parent's methods.

Effectively, the question is saying that we should return true if obj is an instance or descendent of classFunction, **no matter how far up the chain from obj classFunction may be**.

This means that, from our initial Parent/Child/Grandchild code, if we do:
```let child = new Child();
let grandchild = new Grandchild();

console.log(checkIfInstanceOf(grandchild, Child)); 
console.log(checkIfInstanceOf(grandchild, Parent));  
console.log(checkIfInstanceOf(child, Parent)); 
```
All of those console.logs should return "true".

Working code (TS):
```function checkIfInstanceOf(obj: any, classFunction: any): boolean {
    if (obj === null || obj == undefined || typeof classFunction !== "function") return false;
    let potentialPrototype = Object.getPrototypeOf(obj);

    while(potentialPrototype !== null) {
        if (potentialPrototype === (classFunction as Function).prototype) return true;

        potentialPrototype = Object.getPrototypeOf(potentialPrototype);
    }

    return false;

};
```

