# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem requires checking if a given object is an instance of a given class or superclass. One approach is to compare the prototype chain of the object with the prototype of the class.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The `checkIfInstanceOf` function takes two parameters: obj and `classFunction`.

1. First, it checks if either `obj` or `classFunction` is `undefined` or `null`. If so, it returns `false`.
2. Next, it checks if `obj` itself is `null`. If it is, it also returns `false`.
3. Then, it retrieves the prototype of `classFunction` using `classFunction.prototype`.
4. It enters a loop where it checks if obj is equal to the `classPrototype`. If they are equal, it means `obj` has access to the methods of `classFunction`, and the function returns `true`.
5. If the loop completes without finding a match, it means `obj` does not have access to the methods of `classFunction`, and the function returns `false`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: The time complexity of this approach is dependent on the length of the prototype chain of the object. In the worst case, it can be considered as O(n), where n is the length of the prototype chain.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: The space complexity is O(1) as it does not use any additional data structures that grow with the input size.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

