# Intuition
I had to think of a way to come up with a solution without lazily using instanceof

# Approach
Since the prototypes of objects are basically a chain, my initial thought was using some kind of loop to go through the object's prototypes and end it when the nested prototype is null.
Recursion sounded convenient to me so i went with that, and my way of comparing was through the constructors names. i thought of using `Object.getOwnPropertyNames()` then comparing each value of the array, but that's more memory tasking than just accessing the name of the constructor directly with `constructor.name`

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
function checkIfInstanceOf(obj: any, classFn: any): boolean{
    // safety checks
    if(obj === null || classFn === null) return false;
    if(obj === undefined || classFn === undefined) return false;
    return instanceofClass(obj, classFn)
}
function instanceofClass(obj: any, classFn: any): boolean{
    // get the prototype of the value
    const objprototype = Object.getPrototypeOf(obj);
    // get the prototype of the passed class
    const classFnPrototype = classFn.prototype;
    // if classFnPrototype is undefined that means the passed classFn value isn't a class
    if(!classFnPrototype) return false;
    // if we reach the deadend of the object's prototypes, return false
    if(objprototype === null) return false;
    if(objprototype.constructor.name === classFnPrototype.constructor.name) return true;
    const nestedPrototype = Object.getPrototypeOf(obj);
    return instanceofClass(nestedPrototype, classFn)
}
/**
 * checkIfInstanceOf(new Date(), Date); // true
 */
```

